1
00:00:00,900 --> 00:00:04,103
Because Natsuki, you don't really love me.

2
00:00:04,103 --> 00:00:05,138
Wait!

3
00:00:05,138 --> 00:00:06,620
"Getting dumped" means,

4
00:00:06,620 --> 00:00:10,076
being told by someone you like
that they don't like you.

5
00:00:10,076 --> 00:00:12,578
This is Souta Kobayakawa. My boyfriend.

6
00:00:12,578 --> 00:00:14,347
He really is such an unlikable guy.

7
00:00:14,347 --> 00:00:15,348
That's unacceptable!

8
00:00:15,348 --> 00:00:17,276
If you get an E rating on the next mock exam,

9
00:00:17,276 --> 00:00:19,018
you can just give up on
the college entrance exam.

10
00:00:19,018 --> 00:00:20,972
I've been asked to tutor.

11
00:00:20,972 --> 00:00:23,523
<i>But university could still be a catalyst
for some kind of change.</i>

12
00:00:23,523 --> 00:00:25,324
You did well.

13
00:00:25,324 --> 00:00:27,360
[Genuinely falling in love]
This will be my good luck charm, okay?

14
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:32,165
So, the tutoring,
we'll continue with it like this, right?

15
00:00:32,165 --> 00:00:36,688
<i>Together in the summer,
love and storminess came to our home.</i>

16
00:00:44,944 --> 00:00:47,376
[Episode 2]

17
00:00:55,352 --> 00:00:56,989
A tutor, huh?

18
00:00:56,989 --> 00:00:59,932
You got dumped, so you've got nothing to do
during summer vacation but study.

19
00:00:59,932 --> 00:01:01,027
[Natsuki's friend, Ryo Konno]
Shut up.

20
00:01:01,027 --> 00:01:03,262
[Natsuki's friend, Kazuharu Sanada]
I guess I should start getting serious too.

21
00:01:03,262 --> 00:01:05,898
Come with me, Ryo.

22
00:01:05,898 --> 00:01:08,860
- Darn it!
- Whoa, whoa, watch the watermelons!

23
00:01:08,860 --> 00:01:11,404
Students studying to get into college
sure have it rough.

24
00:01:11,404 --> 00:01:14,352
What about you, Kazu?
Have you decided to go to culinary school?

25
00:01:14,352 --> 00:01:17,476
- Yeah.
- You're taking over your dad's restaurant?

26
00:01:17,476 --> 00:01:21,247
I'm going to become a chef
at a three-star restaurant.

27
00:01:21,247 --> 00:01:23,332
- Isn't that cool?
- I prefer your dad's restaurant.

28
00:01:23,332 --> 00:01:25,151
- Why's that?
- Well, me too.

29
00:01:25,151 --> 00:01:28,087
- Your dad's ramen and dumplings are divine!
- I prefer the fried chicken!

30
00:01:28,087 --> 00:01:30,152
- I want the fried chicken!
- I'll have the soy sauce ramen.

31
00:01:30,152 --> 00:01:32,091
Got it.

32
00:01:32,091 --> 00:01:36,128
So you both love fried chicken,
huh, you and your brother Natsuki?

33
00:01:36,128 --> 00:01:37,797
Because it's super delicious.

34
00:01:37,797 --> 00:01:40,933
[Owner of Ryuunken Sanada]
I'm so happy to hear you say that.

35
00:01:40,933 --> 00:01:42,364
- Wait just a moment.
- Sure.

36
00:01:42,364 --> 00:01:43,708
- Soy sauce ramen, fried chicken...
- And then what happened?

37
00:01:43,708 --> 00:01:45,538
[Riyo's friend, Yui Kagami]
What kind of person is Souta?

38
00:01:45,538 --> 00:01:47,532
He's a really nice guy!

39
00:01:47,532 --> 00:01:50,204
So your tutor is Riyo's boyfriend?

40
00:01:50,204 --> 00:01:52,378
Yeah.

41
00:01:52,378 --> 00:01:54,000
What kind of guy is he?

42
00:01:54,780 --> 00:01:56,082
He's insufferable.

43
00:01:56,082 --> 00:01:58,396
"Getting dumped" means,

44
00:01:58,396 --> 00:02:01,132
being told by someone you like
that they don't like you.

45
00:02:01,132 --> 00:02:05,291
He doesn't consider people's feelings.
I guess you could say he lacks delicacy?

46
00:02:05,291 --> 00:02:08,127
He's very kind and considerate.

47
00:02:08,127 --> 00:02:11,597
<i>Is he one of those people who seems to
exude calm intelligence and good upbringing?</i>

48
00:02:11,597 --> 00:02:14,967
The high schooler crying
at the convenience store was Natsuki?

49
00:02:14,967 --> 00:02:17,270
<i>He talks nonstop
about everything all the time.</i>

50
00:02:17,270 --> 00:02:20,668
<i>He has a super charming
killer smile that everybody likes.</i>

51
00:02:20,668 --> 00:02:24,092
<i>But he's also an opportunist
who is good at manipulating people.</i>

52
00:02:24,092 --> 00:02:27,228
- Really? What an insufferable guy.
- Yeah, he really is insufferable.

53
00:02:27,228 --> 00:02:28,252
Right?

54
00:02:28,252 --> 00:02:31,272
- That's just perfect!
- Isn't it?

55
00:02:31,272 --> 00:02:33,719
Why is Riyo with such an insufferable guy?

56
00:02:33,719 --> 00:02:35,484
Is he handsome?

57
00:02:35,484 --> 00:02:37,008
Not really...

58
00:02:37,623 --> 00:02:41,392
But he's good at teaching math.

59
00:02:42,161 --> 00:02:44,016
You did well.

60
00:02:45,116 --> 00:02:48,700
- I'm curious about what kind of guy he is...
- Really?

61
00:02:48,700 --> 00:02:50,640
Calm down.

62
00:02:52,638 --> 00:02:54,736
Oh, looks like there are some rain clouds.

63
00:02:55,341 --> 00:02:58,812
- Rain?
- Yeah, it looks like it'll start raining soon.

64
00:02:58,812 --> 00:03:01,247
- Oh no! Maybe we should head home.
- Yeah.

65
00:03:01,247 --> 00:03:03,449
Natsuki's weather predictions
are always right.

66
00:03:03,449 --> 00:03:05,232
No, I'm not making a forecast.

67
00:03:06,012 --> 00:03:08,208
More like a message from the clouds.

68
00:03:09,596 --> 00:03:12,572
- So cool!
- So cool!

69
00:03:12,572 --> 00:03:14,608
- You guys are making fun of me, aren't you?
- See you.

70
00:03:16,924 --> 00:03:18,512
I'm home.

71
00:03:18,512 --> 00:03:20,872
Natsuki? Souta is here.

72
00:03:20,872 --> 00:03:22,832
Huh? Already?

73
00:03:24,156 --> 00:03:26,288
- It's delicious!
- I know, right?

74
00:03:27,804 --> 00:03:29,884
I'll be teaching you again today.

75
00:03:29,884 --> 00:03:30,940
Thank you in advance.

76
00:03:30,940 --> 00:03:32,764
We ran into each other
at the convenience store.

77
00:03:32,764 --> 00:03:34,608
You're often at the convenience store.

78
00:03:35,314 --> 00:03:38,150
Souta bought me some ice cream. Want some?

79
00:03:38,150 --> 00:03:40,092
- Not right now.
- Oh, okay.

80
00:03:40,092 --> 00:03:42,212
Then I'll take all of it.

81
00:03:42,212 --> 00:03:43,832
I just said not right now.

82
00:03:43,832 --> 00:03:45,712
What a troublesome guy.

83
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:50,940
So you like ice cream, huh, young Natsuki?

84
00:03:50,940 --> 00:03:54,172
You don't need to address him
like that, Souta.

85
00:03:54,172 --> 00:03:56,102
- Why not?
- Because it's a waste.

86
00:03:56,102 --> 00:03:59,388
But suddenly calling someone
just by first name might sound a bit harsh.

87
00:03:59,388 --> 00:04:00,706
You think so?

88
00:04:00,706 --> 00:04:02,541
We aren't that close yet.

89
00:04:02,541 --> 00:04:04,143
I don't like being called that either.

90
00:04:04,143 --> 00:04:06,812
Addressing each other
just by the names will bring you closer.

91
00:04:06,812 --> 00:04:08,047
How you address someone is important.

92
00:04:08,047 --> 00:04:10,320
Yeah, but...

93
00:04:10,950 --> 00:04:12,985
Then how about calling him
'Nat' as a middle ground?

94
00:04:12,985 --> 00:04:14,472
What middle ground?

95
00:04:14,472 --> 00:04:16,508
I guess that might be easier to say
than addressing him just by his first name.

96
00:04:16,508 --> 00:04:18,460
All right, then it's decided.

97
00:04:18,460 --> 00:04:21,052
And how will you address him, Natsuki?

98
00:04:21,052 --> 00:04:22,695
It's fine. I won't call him anything special.

99
00:04:22,695 --> 00:04:26,556
You're younger than him, so calling him
just by his first name feels too forward.

100
00:04:26,556 --> 00:04:30,128
- As for 'Mr.' Souta, that's also...
- That's why I won't call him that.

101
00:04:31,003 --> 00:04:32,938
- How about 'Sou'?
- 'Sou'?

102
00:04:32,938 --> 00:04:34,440
People tend to call me that in my hometown.

103
00:04:34,440 --> 00:04:37,009
Really? Then it's 'Sou' and 'Nat'.

104
00:04:37,009 --> 00:04:39,872
Okay, repeat after me.

105
00:04:39,872 --> 00:04:41,936
Yes, Nat.

106
00:04:43,215 --> 00:04:45,317
Well...

107
00:04:45,317 --> 00:04:47,184
Yes, Sou.

108
00:04:48,572 --> 00:04:49,852
No way.

109
00:04:49,852 --> 00:04:52,112
You two are such buzzkills!

110
00:04:59,365 --> 00:05:01,468
We'll be doing tutoring here today?

111
00:05:01,468 --> 00:05:04,348
Because my sister and parents are around.

112
00:05:04,348 --> 00:05:05,968
I see.

113
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:13,492
Don't stare, it's really messy in here.

114
00:05:13,492 --> 00:05:15,381
Not at all.

115
00:05:15,381 --> 00:05:17,450
I think it's clean.

116
00:05:17,450 --> 00:05:19,552
Go ahead.

117
00:05:19,552 --> 00:05:21,104
Thank you.

118
00:05:28,572 --> 00:05:30,160
Nat...

119
00:05:32,398 --> 00:05:33,532
Natsu...

120
00:05:33,532 --> 00:05:35,692
It's fine, you can call me whatever.

121
00:05:35,692 --> 00:05:39,972
But, as Riyo says, it might bring us closer.

122
00:05:39,972 --> 00:05:43,242
My sister is always so pushy.

123
00:05:43,242 --> 00:05:45,010
How do you even deal with that?

124
00:05:45,010 --> 00:05:47,646
But Riyo is super nice, isn't she?

125
00:05:47,646 --> 00:05:49,456
Is she?

126
00:05:54,119 --> 00:05:56,432
- Natsu...
- What about me?

127
00:05:58,457 --> 00:06:01,456
She was really worried
and came to me for advice.

128
00:06:03,729 --> 00:06:08,240
She wanted me to push you to get started,
saying you have potential.

129
00:06:11,260 --> 00:06:13,104
Really?

130
00:06:20,412 --> 00:06:22,096
All done.

131
00:06:26,012 --> 00:06:29,488
You were close, but just a bit off.

132
00:06:29,488 --> 00:06:31,232
Guess I'm no good at this.

133
00:06:31,232 --> 00:06:33,072
Let's try thinking about this again.

134
00:06:39,565 --> 00:06:41,072
Come in.

135
00:06:42,108 --> 00:06:43,728
All right.

136
00:06:44,470 --> 00:06:46,416
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

137
00:06:47,706 --> 00:06:49,308
How's it going?

138
00:06:49,308 --> 00:06:51,032
Sorry, sir.

139
00:06:51,032 --> 00:06:53,546
Hasn't Mom come back from shopping yet?

140
00:06:53,546 --> 00:06:56,792
She's probably chatting
with the neighbors again.

141
00:06:56,792 --> 00:06:58,817
I wonder if she took an umbrella?

142
00:06:58,817 --> 00:07:01,584
There are nimbostratus clouds,
so I think it might rain.

143
00:07:02,940 --> 00:07:04,592
I see...

144
00:07:05,891 --> 00:07:09,756
All right. Please continue with your lesson.

145
00:07:09,756 --> 00:07:11,344
Okay.

146
00:07:26,612 --> 00:07:28,948
You seem to know a lot about weather, huh?

147
00:07:28,948 --> 00:07:30,649
Why?

148
00:07:30,649 --> 00:07:35,068
Well, the term "nimbostratus clouds"
doesn't exactly roll off the tongue.

149
00:07:35,068 --> 00:07:37,256
But you just said it too.

150
00:07:37,256 --> 00:07:39,856
I'm taking meteorology classes.

151
00:07:41,500 --> 00:07:43,728
Oh? Classes?

152
00:07:44,540 --> 00:07:47,566
Do you want to become
a weather forecaster or something?

153
00:07:47,566 --> 00:07:51,856
I haven't thought that far ahead,
but I'm interested.

154
00:07:55,641 --> 00:07:58,640
- I'll be going out for a bit.
- Okay.

155
00:08:00,913 --> 00:08:03,415
Sounds like he's taking an umbrella
and going to pick her up.

156
00:08:03,415 --> 00:08:05,252
Your mom?

157
00:08:05,252 --> 00:08:06,928
That's so sweet of him.

158
00:08:07,953 --> 00:08:11,632
He's a classic Showa era dad,
though he'd never say that out loud.

159
00:08:12,316 --> 00:08:13,872
I see.

160
00:08:22,172 --> 00:08:23,728
This one's tough.

161
00:08:29,274 --> 00:08:32,400
It's cool after it rains, Rock.

162
00:08:36,508 --> 00:08:38,736
You seem to know a lot about weather, huh?

163
00:08:42,421 --> 00:08:45,360
He might be sharper than he looks.

164
00:08:51,096 --> 00:08:53,065
What's up?

165
00:08:53,065 --> 00:08:55,216
You're so cute, Rock.

166
00:09:15,688 --> 00:09:19,152
[You have a new message from Souta]
Did we exchange contacts?

167
00:09:20,764 --> 00:09:22,352
Hold on.

168
00:09:23,028 --> 00:09:25,197
Feel free to let me know
if you have any questions.

169
00:09:25,197 --> 00:09:27,665
Okay. I probably won't, though.

170
00:09:29,404 --> 00:09:31,603
I did.

171
00:09:31,603 --> 00:09:36,124
<i>Good morning.
Today, let's go on a field trip.</i>

172
00:09:36,124 --> 00:09:37,968
A field trip?

173
00:09:57,604 --> 00:09:58,872
Hello.

174
00:09:58,872 --> 00:10:00,974
It's nice being outside.

175
00:10:00,974 --> 00:10:03,010
Why do you seem so fresh
when it's scorching hot out?

176
00:10:03,010 --> 00:10:04,578
Thanks.

177
00:10:04,578 --> 00:10:06,246
I wasn't complimenting you.

178
00:10:06,246 --> 00:10:08,949
I don't believe in genuinely pleasant people.

179
00:10:08,949 --> 00:10:10,784
Why not?

180
00:10:10,784 --> 00:10:13,296
I just think it's an act.

181
00:10:14,087 --> 00:10:15,889
An act, huh?

182
00:10:15,889 --> 00:10:17,756
You're not denying it.

183
00:10:17,756 --> 00:10:21,295
- Hey, Natsuki!
- Hey, Riku.

184
00:10:21,295 --> 00:10:23,096
Did you get dumped again, Natsuki?

185
00:10:23,096 --> 00:10:24,364
What? No, I didn't.

186
00:10:24,364 --> 00:10:27,267
- You're not crying, right?
- I'm actually quite popular, you know.

187
00:10:27,267 --> 00:10:30,170
Oh! It's that teacher from the other day!

188
00:10:30,170 --> 00:10:32,472
Well, I'm not actually a teacher.

189
00:10:32,472 --> 00:10:35,676
- Hello.
- Teacher, what does it mean to be popular?

190
00:10:35,676 --> 00:10:37,244
Hey. You can ask me that, you know.

191
00:10:37,244 --> 00:10:39,680
But this teacher explains things clearly.

192
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:41,968
- Huh?
- Well...

193
00:10:43,083 --> 00:10:48,355
It means someone whom lots of people like.

194
00:10:48,355 --> 00:10:52,080
- Then Natsuki isn't popular.
- Why not?

195
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:53,648
Because you got dumped.

196
00:10:54,680 --> 00:10:55,830
"Getting dumped" means,

197
00:10:55,830 --> 00:10:58,865
being told by someone you like
that they don't like you, right?

198
00:10:58,865 --> 00:11:01,308
You remembered that very well.

199
00:11:01,308 --> 00:11:03,568
Good job.

200
00:11:06,006 --> 00:11:07,696
You did well.

201
00:11:08,809 --> 00:11:10,236
More, more.

202
00:11:10,236 --> 00:11:12,336
You're great.

203
00:11:13,914 --> 00:11:16,883
<i>Riku isn't fazed by it at all.</i>

204
00:11:16,883 --> 00:11:19,824
<i>Am I weird for being startled by it?</i>

205
00:11:36,636 --> 00:11:39,216
You like clouds, don't you?

206
00:11:40,107 --> 00:11:42,928
- What?
- Even your strap looks like a cloud.

207
00:11:43,543 --> 00:11:44,640
Not really.

208
00:11:44,640 --> 00:11:46,320
What? Really?

209
00:11:47,214 --> 00:11:49,232
This is a Samoyed.

210
00:11:50,817 --> 00:11:53,253
I see.

211
00:11:53,253 --> 00:11:55,560
I thought it was a cloud with a face.

212
00:11:55,560 --> 00:12:00,880
It's a Samoyed, but I guess it does
kind of look similar to a cloud.

213
00:12:00,880 --> 00:12:02,416
Yeah.

214
00:12:06,299 --> 00:12:10,128
Look, doesn't that cloud over there
look just like a Samoyed?

215
00:12:10,904 --> 00:12:13,200
What? Which cloud?

216
00:12:14,541 --> 00:12:16,048
That one.

217
00:12:17,778 --> 00:12:21,782
Ah... now that you mention it,
it does kind of look like a Samoyed.

218
00:12:21,782 --> 00:12:23,784
Right?

219
00:12:23,784 --> 00:12:26,224
Do you know what they call that?

220
00:12:27,516 --> 00:12:29,040
What do you mean, "that"?

221
00:12:29,948 --> 00:12:34,061
When clouds look like people or animals.

222
00:12:34,061 --> 00:12:35,868
There's a name for that?

223
00:12:35,868 --> 00:12:37,698
Yeah.

224
00:12:37,698 --> 00:12:39,568
It's called pareidolia.

225
00:12:40,700 --> 00:12:42,288
Pai... Pai?

226
00:12:43,036 --> 00:12:44,784
Pareidolia.

227
00:12:47,174 --> 00:12:50,332
Like seeing a rabbit in the moon.

228
00:12:50,332 --> 00:12:53,104
Or seeing a human face in rocks.
That's the same phenomenon.

229
00:12:54,940 --> 00:12:57,417
Even though we know it's something different,

230
00:12:57,417 --> 00:13:00,624
it's a psychological phenomenon
where we see it as something familiar.

231
00:13:02,364 --> 00:13:06,426
Pa... Pa... Pareidolia?

232
00:13:06,426 --> 00:13:08,995
Pareidolia, huh?

233
00:13:08,995 --> 00:13:10,748
That's it.

234
00:13:10,748 --> 00:13:12,700
What?

235
00:13:12,700 --> 00:13:14,935
- Let's call it a day for math.
- What?

236
00:13:14,935 --> 00:13:18,320
Let's switch this to
a meteorology class from here.

237
00:13:18,320 --> 00:13:19,856
Huh?

238
00:13:20,520 --> 00:13:22,442
- Here's your fried chicken.
- Hey, hey.

239
00:13:22,442 --> 00:13:26,896
I heard that Souta is smart,
kind, and just the best guy.

240
00:13:28,148 --> 00:13:30,812
Huh? But isn't he really insensitive?

241
00:13:30,812 --> 00:13:34,621
Yeah, yeah. He's good at teaching math,

242
00:13:34,621 --> 00:13:36,156
but he's kind of an unpleasant guy.

243
00:13:36,156 --> 00:13:39,025
Huh? That's totally different
from what Riyo said.

244
00:13:39,025 --> 00:13:40,360
Here you go, your fried rice.

245
00:13:40,360 --> 00:13:43,563
- Here you go, your fried rice.
- Thank you.

246
00:13:43,563 --> 00:13:47,834
People can seem completely different
depending on your perspective.

247
00:13:47,834 --> 00:13:50,137
Can I write that down, sir?

248
00:13:50,137 --> 00:13:52,305
Sure! Everyone, write that down! Copy it!

249
00:13:52,305 --> 00:13:53,916
- Engrave it...
- Engrave it in your heart.

250
00:13:53,916 --> 00:13:55,642
I'll do that!

251
00:13:55,642 --> 00:13:59,312
What kind of guy is Riyo's boyfriend?

252
00:14:00,614 --> 00:14:02,249
What about this one?

253
00:14:02,249 --> 00:14:04,117
- Cumulonimbus clouds.
- Correct!

254
00:14:04,117 --> 00:14:08,040
These clouds grow quickly
and cause sudden thunderstorms.

255
00:14:08,040 --> 00:14:09,623
They're quite the opposite
of nimbostratus clouds.

256
00:14:09,623 --> 00:14:11,525
Correct.

257
00:14:11,525 --> 00:14:13,426
Give me something more challenging.

258
00:14:13,426 --> 00:14:15,984
Wow, you're motivated.

259
00:14:20,333 --> 00:14:21,902
What about this one?

260
00:14:21,902 --> 00:14:25,872
Well... what's that one again?

261
00:14:25,872 --> 00:14:28,656
Well...

262
00:14:30,310 --> 00:14:31,912
Can I have a hint?

263
00:14:31,912 --> 00:14:33,380
It starts with an 'a'.

264
00:14:33,380 --> 00:14:35,888
A... A...

265
00:14:36,817 --> 00:14:39,820
- Anvil cloud!
- Correct!

266
00:14:39,820 --> 00:14:42,480
- That's impressive.
- Next one.

267
00:14:46,293 --> 00:14:48,112
How do you count clouds?

268
00:14:49,196 --> 00:14:51,631
- One cloud, two clouds?
- No.

269
00:14:51,631 --> 00:14:53,733
It differs depending on the type of cloud.

270
00:14:53,733 --> 00:14:55,335
- Really?
- Yeah.

271
00:14:55,335 --> 00:14:58,800
For example... one spot of cloud.

272
00:14:59,439 --> 00:15:01,520
One streak of cloud.

273
00:15:02,275 --> 00:15:03,484
One piece of cloud.

274
00:15:03,484 --> 00:15:06,746
Wow, I didn't know that.

275
00:15:06,746 --> 00:15:11,650
The more you learn about clouds,
the deeper it gets.

276
00:15:12,452 --> 00:15:15,920
<i>That sparkling must be due to the light.</i>

277
00:15:18,844 --> 00:15:21,200
- Thanks for the meal.
- Thank you.

278
00:15:25,465 --> 00:15:27,440
[Great job]
You did well today too.

279
00:15:28,740 --> 00:15:31,271
Huh? But I didn't really do anything today.

280
00:15:31,271 --> 00:15:33,180
You studied.

281
00:15:33,180 --> 00:15:34,975
What?

282
00:15:34,975 --> 00:15:38,992
Learning new things and things
you didn't know before, counts as studying.

283
00:15:39,713 --> 00:15:41,776
But it's not math.

284
00:15:42,415 --> 00:15:44,551
That's okay.

285
00:15:44,551 --> 00:15:48,054
If you can find the joy in studying,
it leads to the next step.

286
00:15:48,054 --> 00:15:51,091
When I was trying to do that,
I thought I'd start with something you like.

287
00:15:51,091 --> 00:15:52,944
Is that why you're taking
that extracurricular class?

288
00:15:55,729 --> 00:15:58,256
[Introduction to Meteorology]

289
00:15:59,366 --> 00:16:02,202
I'm glad you like clouds.

290
00:16:02,202 --> 00:16:04,304
It would've been rough if I got it wrong.

291
00:16:07,932 --> 00:16:12,112
Is there a reason why you like clouds?

292
00:16:17,484 --> 00:16:19,551
Are you listening?

293
00:16:24,092 --> 00:16:25,968
Wh... What was that again?

294
00:16:27,627 --> 00:16:30,096
I asked you, why do you like clouds?

295
00:16:31,560 --> 00:16:34,034
<i>I'm not feeling nervous or anything.</i>

296
00:16:34,034 --> 00:16:36,403
Well...

297
00:16:36,403 --> 00:16:38,864
<i>Definitely not.</i>

298
00:16:47,747 --> 00:16:53,253
This is the place where
I first started liking clouds.

299
00:16:53,253 --> 00:16:55,376
I see.

300
00:16:56,156 --> 00:17:02,224
When I was a kid, I used to come here with
my sister and dad to watch planes take off.

301
00:17:03,164 --> 00:17:07,334
I wonder if your plane is here yet, Dad.

302
00:17:07,334 --> 00:17:11,271
It's not my plane,
it's the plane I worked on.

303
00:17:11,271 --> 00:17:14,672
So doesn't that make it your plane, Dad?

304
00:17:15,575 --> 00:17:18,600
- Oh, there it is!
- You're right!

305
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:20,444
I wonder where it's going.

306
00:17:20,444 --> 00:17:23,350
At this time of day,
it must be the flight to Fukuoka.

307
00:17:23,350 --> 00:17:26,519
It goes to the other side
of the sea, very far away.

308
00:17:26,519 --> 00:17:28,080
Cool!

309
00:17:28,080 --> 00:17:30,620
Those clouds are interesting!

310
00:17:30,620 --> 00:17:33,540
- Those are contrails, right?
- Yeah.

311
00:17:33,540 --> 00:17:35,628
Today they're lingering without disappearing.

312
00:17:35,628 --> 00:17:38,565
Which means it might rain later.

313
00:17:38,565 --> 00:17:40,266
Why?

314
00:17:40,266 --> 00:17:43,164
Because it's proof that
the humidity in the sky is high.

315
00:17:43,164 --> 00:17:47,907
- Wow, so the clouds are telling us that?
- Exactly.

316
00:17:47,907 --> 00:17:50,343
It's a message from the sky.

317
00:17:50,343 --> 00:17:53,480
- Amazing!
- Cool!

318
00:17:53,480 --> 00:17:55,376
Yeah, it's really cool!

319
00:17:58,551 --> 00:18:04,090
That's when I thought that
clouds are really something.

320
00:18:04,090 --> 00:18:05,744
That's a good story.

321
00:18:07,260 --> 00:18:09,095
It's nothing special.

322
00:18:09,095 --> 00:18:11,888
You have a great dad, and a great family too.

323
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,804
What about you? Something happened, right?

324
00:18:17,804 --> 00:18:21,741
Something that makes studying fun,
or something you like.

325
00:18:21,741 --> 00:18:23,920
Is it okay if I talk about myself?

326
00:18:24,700 --> 00:18:27,080
Yeah, of course.

327
00:18:27,080 --> 00:18:29,328
Then would you mind
spending a little time with me?

328
00:18:30,350 --> 00:18:31,920
Sure.

329
00:18:33,064 --> 00:18:34,532
[Ryuunken Sanada]
All right, please take care of this.

330
00:18:34,532 --> 00:18:36,059
Looks tasty.

331
00:18:36,059 --> 00:18:41,038
- Sorry, my dad can be demanding.
- It's fine, it's on my way home anyway.

332
00:18:41,038 --> 00:18:42,043
Oh, Natsuki.

333
00:18:42,043 --> 00:18:44,731
Oh, is that the rumored tutor?

334
00:18:44,731 --> 00:18:47,145
Is that Riyo's boyfriend?

335
00:18:47,145 --> 00:18:49,981
Natsuki doesn't seem to mind him.

336
00:18:49,981 --> 00:18:52,150
- True, it seems like they're having fun.
- Yeah.

337
00:18:52,150 --> 00:18:53,711
Another lie...

338
00:18:55,386 --> 00:18:57,555
Here we are.

339
00:18:57,555 --> 00:18:59,223
Huh? Here?

340
00:18:59,223 --> 00:19:01,551
Yeah, the bridge.

341
00:19:02,460 --> 00:19:04,395
What about the bridge?

342
00:19:04,395 --> 00:19:06,063
It's something I like.

343
00:19:06,831 --> 00:19:10,501
- This bridge?
- No, not just this bridge.

344
00:19:10,501 --> 00:19:14,159
From small bridges to big bridges...
all bridges, actually.

345
00:19:15,591 --> 00:19:17,679
Why do you like bridges?

346
00:19:19,739 --> 00:19:22,939
Bridges span rivers, seas, valleys, roads,

347
00:19:22,939 --> 00:19:25,839
connecting places that are otherwise divided.

348
00:19:29,020 --> 00:19:30,931
Okay, stay right there!

349
00:19:30,931 --> 00:19:32,783
Huh? Okay.

350
00:19:33,787 --> 00:19:35,407
What?

351
00:19:46,211 --> 00:19:49,263
Nat!

352
00:19:53,511 --> 00:19:56,031
If this bridge didn't exist,

353
00:19:56,031 --> 00:19:58,031
we might still be able to see each other,

354
00:19:58,651 --> 00:20:00,815
but we wouldn't be able to get closer, right?

355
00:20:05,531 --> 00:20:07,055
But...

356
00:20:09,755 --> 00:20:11,503
Huh? What?

357
00:20:20,905 --> 00:20:25,039
Thanks to this bridge, we can meet like this.

358
00:20:28,112 --> 00:20:31,087
Bridges connect people.

359
00:20:34,051 --> 00:20:39,471
Maybe hundreds of years from now,
all of Japan... no,

360
00:20:40,291 --> 00:20:43,919
maybe even the whole world
might be connected by bridges.

361
00:20:46,264 --> 00:20:49,871
It sounds like a dream,
but wouldn't that be amazing?

362
00:21:04,795 --> 00:21:06,639
I wonder where that bridge is.

363
00:21:07,739 --> 00:21:10,411
<i>I wonder where that bridge is.</i>

364
00:21:10,411 --> 00:21:14,158
- Huh?
- Do you know what that bridge is?

365
00:21:14,158 --> 00:21:17,395
Yeah, it's the Sokolullu Mehmet Pasha Bridge.

366
00:21:17,395 --> 00:21:19,759
Sokolullu Mehmet Pasha.

367
00:21:20,431 --> 00:21:23,291
A World Heritage Site of the Ottoman Empire.

368
00:21:23,291 --> 00:21:27,503
Wow, I didn't know that. Thanks.

369
00:21:30,141 --> 00:21:35,112
- Well... I...
- Oh. My surname is Kobayakawa.

370
00:21:35,112 --> 00:21:36,580
I'm in the same class as you.

371
00:21:36,580 --> 00:21:38,575
- Huh? The same class?
- Yeah.

372
00:21:39,283 --> 00:21:42,186
Sorry, I'm not that good
at remembering faces.

373
00:21:42,186 --> 00:21:43,854
No problem.

374
00:21:43,854 --> 00:21:45,056
You like bridges?

375
00:21:45,056 --> 00:21:47,625
Yeah, I really love them.

376
00:21:47,625 --> 00:21:50,227
- Okay, do you want to have lunch together?
- Huh?

377
00:21:50,227 --> 00:21:53,751
I'm a World Heritage enthusiast.
We may have some interesting conversations.

378
00:21:53,751 --> 00:21:55,952
Yeah, I agree.

379
00:21:57,868 --> 00:22:04,367
I want to go to
Sokolullu Mehmet Pasha Bridge with Souta.

380
00:22:06,277 --> 00:22:11,823
Once I start talking about bridges,
I can't see anything else and just go crazy.

381
00:22:12,483 --> 00:22:14,218
I'm sorry.

382
00:22:14,218 --> 00:22:17,722
No, I think it's really great.

383
00:22:17,722 --> 00:22:19,279
What?

384
00:22:20,124 --> 00:22:24,562
I didn't really think much
about bridges before,

385
00:22:24,562 --> 00:22:27,131
but now I'm pretty interested.

386
00:22:27,131 --> 00:22:28,847
- Really?
- Yeah.

387
00:22:29,967 --> 00:22:33,137
Having something you love so much,

388
00:22:33,137 --> 00:22:36,047
and being able to talk passionately
about it is really great.

389
00:22:37,041 --> 00:22:39,343
- Is that so?
- Yeah.

390
00:22:40,811 --> 00:22:42,863
That simply makes me very happy.

391
00:22:46,684 --> 00:22:51,055
<i>Something was starting to stir within me.</i>

392
00:22:55,426 --> 00:22:59,163
So you want to build bridges?
Is that why you're studying at university?

393
00:22:59,163 --> 00:23:01,531
Yeah, that's my dream.

394
00:23:01,531 --> 00:23:03,701
That's awesome.

395
00:23:03,701 --> 00:23:05,787
I'm happy!

396
00:23:05,787 --> 00:23:09,199
Only you and Riyo ever say things
like that to me.

397
00:23:11,675 --> 00:23:16,143
<i>But this person is my sister's boyfriend.</i>

398
00:23:17,415 --> 00:23:20,239
<i>For a moment, I almost forgot.</i>

